name: leg-land-dummy
html:
Well Done!

You are landed on a safe page!

The sender email is from a legitimate domain and the link contained in this email was pointing to a legitimate webpage.

name: it1-phish-land
html:
You are landed on a malicious page!

The attackers use several tricks in a phishing email to mislead you.

You should have paid attention to the following "Phishing" indicators:

 

  1. The Email context looks strange with big bold and coloured text parts. It appears not professionaly correct.

  2. The email domain is fake: The email displayed is "no_reply26646-delivery26646-patch26646@office.365.com". This is not a legitimate email domain from microsoft. Notice the long sender part that helps to confuse even more the user.

  3.  Spoofed URL: If you hover above the link contained in the email <Clean Up Now::> , you will see displayed at the bottom left of the email window, that the actual page url is http://office.365.com. The legitimate domain name from Microsoft https://office.live.com.

  4. Notice the HTTP usage instead of the secure HTTPS on the redirected malicious url http://office.365.com.

name: it2-phish-land
html:
You are landed on a malicious page!

The attackers use several tricks in a phishing email to mislead you.

You should have paid attention to the following "Phishing" indicators:

 

  1. Unprofessional email design: The Email context looks strange with big bold and coloured text parts. It appears not professional.

  2. The email domain is fake: The email displayed is "no-reply@office.365.com". This is not a legitimate email domain from microsoft.

  3. Sence of urgency: The email context has a sense of urgency that rushes the user to take the suggested actions asap.

  4.  Spoofed URL: The email lilnk is displayed as https://office.live.com/login. However if you hover above the link, you will see displayed at the bottom left the actual page url used by the sender, which is the fake http://office.365.com.

  5. Notice the HTTP usage instead of the secure HTTPS on the redirected malicious url http://office.365.com.

name: it4-phish-land
html:
You are landed on a malicious page!

The attackers use several tricks in a phishing email to mislead you.

 

 This is internal email address: Somehow the attacker got access to the credentials of an internal email account and uses it to target the contacts of the stolen account. You can verify that the original email sender uses a legitimate internal account:double click the sender display name to crosscheck that the display name is the same as the sender.<@kernelcars.com>.

You should have paid attention to the following "Phishing" indicators:

  1. General addressing: The email domain is fake: The email displayed to recipient is ""training-kernelcars.com"which is different from the legitimate company email domain "training.kernelcars.com".

  2. Spoofed url: The email link displays the url "https://training.kernelcars.com/courses", however if you hover above the link you will notice at the bottom left that the actual url page is "http://training-kernelcars.com/cources".

  3. Notice the HTTP: Tpresence on the actual redirection page. This in not HTTPS and thus not secure page to visit.

In order to get the original email source you need to double click the sender display name and thus reveal the original email source <ot@kernel-cars.com>.

  2. Spoofed URL: If you hover above the link contained in the email https://motor.scada.kernelcars.com/password-update , you will see displayed at the bottom left of the page, that the actual page url is http://motor.scada.kernel-cars.com/password-update. Observed the difference?

  3. Notice the HTTP usage instead of the secure HTTPS on the redirected malicious url http://motor.scada.kernel-cars.com/password-update.

  4. Presense of spelling errors in the email text: eg costumer, ingeneering, folowing etc.

name: it3-phish-land
html:
You are landed on a malicious page!

The attackers use several tricks in a phishing email to mislead you.

 

 This is internal email address: Somehow the attacker got access to the credentials of an internal email account and uses it to target the contacts of the stolen account. You can verify that the original email sender uses a legitimate internal account:double click the sender display name to crosscheck that the display name is the same as the sender.<@kernelcars.com>.

You should have paid attention to the following "Phishing" indicators:

  1. General addressing: The sender that is supposed to be a collegue at the same company,refers to the recipient with a general strange salutation "Dear coworker", instead of using your name for example.

  2. Sense of Urgency: The email context has a sense of urgency that rushes the user to act and download the file.

  3. Malicious attachment: The email contains a pdf file that is malicious. Once the user downloads and opens the file, a malicious script runs on the backround and set a remote network communication between the attacker and your pc (Not shown in this scenario).
